<Article
  title="Building Your Own Game Knowledge System That Actually Lasts"
  description="Stop relying on random guides that go stale. Build a lightweight personal system to capture and organize what matters for the games you actually play."
  kicker="Long-term Play"
  date="2026-06-24"
  heading="Building a Personal Knowledge System"
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="sec">
    <p>Most serious players eventually realize that external guides are great for getting started but terrible for long-term mastery. The meta changes, the guides get abandoned, and you’re left with fragmented notes in five different Discord servers.</p>
    <p>A personal knowledge system fixes this. It doesn’t need to be complicated.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>The minimal structure that works</h2>
    <ul class="kv">
      <li><strong>One page per major topic</strong> (e.g., “Moon X routes”, “Bracken counters”, “Best early items”).</li>
      <li><strong>Version tag at the top</strong> of every note.</li>
      <li><strong>Uncertainty flag</strong> for anything you haven’t personally verified.</li>
      <li><strong>One “why this works” sentence</strong> — not just the tactic, but the reason.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>Tools that actually survive</h2>
    <p>Pick something you will still be using in six months:</p>
    <ul class="kv">
      <li>Simple markdown files in a folder (Obsidian, Notion, or even a private repo).</li>
      <li>One shared document per game with your group if you play together a lot.</li>
      <li>Avoid: random screenshots, Discord message history, browser bookmarks.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>The habit that makes it useful</h2>
    <p>After every session where something important happened (new discovery, painful mistake, patch that broke your route), spend 90 seconds writing it down with context. Do this immediately — not “later”.</p>
    <p>Over a few weeks you will have something more accurate and personalized than 90% of public guides.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec next">
    <p>Pair this with our guide on <a href="/en/articles/reading-game-patch-notes">reading patch notes effectively</a> and you stop being surprised by updates.</p>
  </section>
</Article>
